But its not possible to tell which line is Russia and which is USA. So I am going to color Russia red and USA blue.

USA %>% 
  ggplot()+
   geom_line(aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons))+
  geom_line(data = Russia,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour =  "Russia"))+
  geom_line(data = USA,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour = "USA"))+
  scale_colour_manual("", values = c("Russia"="red", "USA"="blue")) +

       y= "Newclear weapon possession",
       x="Year")

Now its easy to see the weapon stockpiles of both countries. It doesnt look so scary today as when the Cold War was at its peak in the 1980s. ##Nuclear disarmament agreements If we look at the nuclear weapons on a historical perspective again, i would like to see if the six disarmament agreements between USA and Russia has any effect on the American and Russian nuclear stockpiles during the Cold War. After the Cold Warss ending, the two super powers made three more disarmament agreements. The disarmament agreements were in the years of 1963, 1968, 1972, 1979, 1987, 1991, 1993, 2002, 2010. I used this https://www.discoverbits.in/2373/r-how-to-add-legend-to-geom_vline-in-ggplot webside to get the code for the dotted lines who symbolises the disarmament agreements.

USA %>% 
  ggplot()+
   geom_line(aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons))+
  geom_line(data = Russia,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour =  "Russia"))+
  geom_line(data = USA,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour = "USA"))+
  scale_colour_manual("", values = c("Russia"="red", "USA"="blue")) +
  labs(title = "USA and Russia",
       y= "Newclear weapon possession",
       x="Year")+
   geom_vline(xintercept = c( 1963, 1968, 1972, 1979, 1987, 1991, 1993, 2002, 2010), linetype = "dotted")

We can see on this visualization that Russia didnt really disarm their nuclear stockpile in connection with the first four disarmament agreements. But in 1987 can we see a drastic change. USA did as well. This was the INF-agreement (Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces), and apparently after that, the Russian stockpile was reduced significantly. I want to mark that out on my visualization. For that i used the code from this webside: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/change-font-size-for-annotation-using-ggplot2-in-r/ I also added all the years from 1945-2022 on the y-axis to make it easier to see the development throughout the years.

USA %>% 
  ggplot()+
   geom_line(aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons))+
  geom_line(data = Russia,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour =  "Russia"))+
  geom_line(data = USA,aes(x=Year, y= Nuclear_weapons, colour = "USA"))+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1963, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1968, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1972, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1979, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1987, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1991, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  1993, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  2002, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept =  2010, color = "Disarmament Agreements"), linetype = "dashed") +
  annotate("text", x= 1987, y= 30000, label = "INF-agreement", angle = 90, size= 4) +
  scale_colour_manual("", values = c("Russia"="red", "USA"="blue", "Disarmament Agreements"="grey")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = .5, hjust=.5, size = 6)) +
  scale_x_continuous("Year", labels = USA$Year, breaks = USA$Year)+
  labs(title = "USA and Russia",
       y= "Newclear weapon possession",
       x="Year")

##Conclusion I can now conclude off of my visualizations, that the disarmament agreements didnt make Russia reduce their nuclear stockpile, before the INF-agreement in 1987. Actually the Russian nuclear stockpile grew drastically until the INF-agreement. After the Cold War ended in 1991, the possessions of nuclear weapons decreased both for USA and Russia.
